# Intuition
If you see , problem statement we have to find subarray which is in ascending order and have maximum sum.
What are known points:
    1. An array of Integers which will contain subarray in ascending order having maximum sum.
    2. Their will subarray which have maximum sum , it could be single element, or actual subarray.(**What is a subarray ?** Answer: A subarray is a contiguous part of array, i.e., Subarray is an array that is inside another array.)
    3. The subarray should be in ascending order, in which single element subarray can also be consider as ascending order, and also if you find subarray size > 0 having maximum sum Let say Example {a, b ,c} then a<b<c strictly.

Gathering all known things , we can think about start pointer and end pointer approach, where

start = 0
end = 1
tempSum = nums[start]
ans = 0
Traverse through nums array with condition start <= end && end < n

>1. if current element is greater than previous element (following ascending order rule) , add the values to temporary sum and maximize the answer , Increase end pointer by one

>2. else we will make start point as end and end pointer to next of start i.e (start + 1), maximize the answer, reset temporary sum value to nums[start].

Don't Forget the Edge Case which is not covered in iteration:
if length of array is equal to 1 then return nums[0]

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int maxAscendingSum(int[] nums) {

        int start = 0;
        int end = 1;
        int n = nums.length;
        if(n == 1) {
            return nums[0];
        }
        int ans = 0;
        int s = nums[0];
        while(start <= end && end < n) {
            if(nums[end] > nums[end - 1]) {
                s += nums[end];
                ans = Math.max(ans, s);
                end ++;
            } else {
                start = end;
                end = start + 1;
                ans = Math.max(ans, s);
                s = nums[start];
            }

        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```
